%U A397446 1,4,3,7,2,2,4,6,10,0,7,4,15,7,2,5,8,2,4
%N A397446 a(n) is the number of distinct primitive, simple, nondegenerate, integer-sided quadrilaterals with both diagonals integral and integer area, having semiperimeter n.
%C A397446 Primitive means gcd(a, b, c, d, e, f) = 1, where a, b, c, d are the side lengths in cyclic order and e and f are the diagonals.
%C A397446 A quadrilateral is represented by the cyclic side sequence (a, b, c, d) modulo D4 together with the unordered diagonal pair {e, f}; distinct quadrilaterals correspond to distinct such pairs.
%C A397446 Every counted quadrilateral decomposes along a diagonal into two Heronian triangles. Their areas may be integral or half-integral, but their sum (the area of the quadrilateral) is an integer. Since every Heronian triangle has even perimeter, the quadrilateral perimeter (a + b + e) + (c + d + e) - 2*e = a + b + c + d is also even; hence the sequence is indexed by the semiperimeter n = (a + b + c + d)/2.
%H A397446 Felix Huber, <a href="/A397446/a397446.txt">Maple program</a>.
%H A397446 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HeronsFormula.html">Heron's Formula</a>.
%F A397446 a(n) = A397447(n) + A397448(n).
%F A397446 a(n) <= Sum_{k=1..2*n} A344529(k).
%e A397446 a(10) = 1: [5, 5, 5, 5; {6, 8}].
%e A397446 a(33) = 6: [7, 15, 20, 24; {20, 25}], [7, 15, 24, 20; {15, 20}], [7, 20, 15, 24; {15, 25}], [13, 13, 20, 20; {21, 24}], [13, 14, 15, 24; {13, 15}], [13, 20, 13, 20; {11, 21}].
